{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491366"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:44:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"922"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/922"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.31,0.06,0.12,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/922"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"922"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26891"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"403"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39407"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents with a one-week history of fever associated with shivers and chills. Two days before admission she developed right-sided abdominal pain. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes and rheumatoid arthritis. On examination her blood pressure is 134/76 mmHg, pulse 92/min and temperature 38.3\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her abdomen is soft, apart from some tenderness in her right flank. An ultrasound scan shows a hypoechoic mass in the right kidney measuring 2.8cm. This is further defined by a CT scan (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antibiotics","Percutaneous drainage","Nephrectomy","Antipyretics and analgesics","Surgical drainage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with a history of fever associated with shivers, chills and right-sided abdominal pain which is almost certainly a consequence of the pathological process seen in the right kidney. The CT scan shows the mass is seen extending from the renal parenchyma outside the kidney and is associated with stranding of the perinephric tissues. These findings are most suggestive of a renal abscess. This will be secondary to an ascending urinary infection. When smaller than 3cm, these abscesses can be treated in the first instance with \u003Cstrong\u003Eantibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E can be employed simultaneously with antibiotics treatment. This approach is usually only necessary when the abscess is bigger than 3cm in size. Percutaneous catheter drainage can be used if symptoms and radiographic abnormality persist after several days of appropriate antibiotics treatment of an abscess smaller than 3cm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntipyretics and analgesics\u003C/strong\u003E alone are not going to control the disease process because the prime cause is an infective process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is usually employed when both antibiotics and percutaneous drainage have failed to resolve the abscess or when the abscess is very large in size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENephrectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is usually employed in patients with chronically infected and atrophic kidneys that develop a perinephric abscess.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Antibiotics are the treatment of choice in a small perinephric or renal abscess."],"references":["Okafor CN, Onyeaso EE. Perinephric Abscess. [Updated 2022 Aug 22]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26891"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"922"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18751"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18751"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7375eca7-cded-4bf5-89cf-3c240eaf9c06.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7375eca7-cded-4bf5-89cf-3c240eaf9c06.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":526,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26891"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-27T12:49:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T20:45:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"922"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41914"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://ap